{"id":20216, "kind":"Bug", "createdAt":"2012-12-06T08:48:56.859455-08:00", "status":"Closed", "title":"ResourceServices.getServices is undocumented", "category":"documentation", "severity":"Major", "priority":{"level":"5", "title":""}, "submittedBy":{"username":"kcoleman", "name":"Kim Coleman", "email":"kim.coleman@marklogic.com"}, "assignTo":{"username":"nobody", "name":"nobody nobody", "email":"nobody@marklogic.com"}, "description":"com.marklogic.client.extensions.ResourceManager.getServices() is absolutely required to use a resource extension from a Java application. It's use is demonstrated by com.marklogic.client.cookbook.ResourceExtension, but the method is completely invisible and undocumented to the user. If you didn't have the example to look at, you wouldn't know it exists, and even that leaves you going \"WTF?\"\r\n\r\nErik and I looked into it. The problem is that getservices() is a protected method of ResourceManager. The notion is that only the dev writing a wrapper class around an extension should have to know about the method. All true, and all good, except that protected methods are not  exposed by javadoc. In most cases, that's desirable behavior, but not here, where the method is user-facing.\r\n\r\nThere's no way in javadoc to cherry pick the function and we don't want to expose the rest of the protected methods in the API, so we'll just have to manually document the interface and its purpose in the description of ResourceManager in the javadoc.\r\n", "samplequery":"", "sampledata":"", "version":"6.0-nightly", "tofixin":"6.0-3", "fixedin":"6.0-3", "platform":"all", "memory":"", "processors":"", "note":"", "subscribers":[{"username":"kcoleman", "name":"Kim Coleman", "email":"kim.coleman@marklogic.com"}], "attachments":[], "relationships":[{"type":"", "to":""}], "clones":[], "cloneOf":"", "support":{"headline":"", "supportDescription":"", "publishStatus":"Never Publish", "tickets":[], "customerImpact":{"level":"N/A", "title":""}, "workaround":""}, 